{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df5b2997-394b-420a-ba64-300aaba26f91","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01BEA2SsoHKnS7kL6PAmnrhp","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Providing MAUI Android setup plan"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01NMmcJ8jmKTZTWAarRPpezc","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -3","description":"Check installed .NET SDK version","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check installed .NET SDK version"}],"interactionId":"ba5a5087-7245-4b33-9568-673a87dc8cb8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a specific plan for setting up a MAUI Android build environment on a headless Linux CI server. They have .NET SDK but nothing else. Let me provide a concrete, actionable plan.\n\nLet me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **Java/JDK** - Android build tools require JDK 11+\n2. **Android SDK** - Command-line tools, platform tools, build tools, platform APIs\n3. **Android workload for .NET** - `dotnet workload install maui-android` or `android`\n4. **.NET MAUI workload**\n5. **Environment variables** - JAVA_HOME, ANDROID_HOME/ANDROID_SDK_ROOT\n\n\nThe tricky part is getting the versions to align properly. The MAUI workload determines which Android API level and build-tools are required, while the Android workload manifest specifies the JDK version needed. I can check `dotnet workload search` and examine the workload manifests to figure out the exact dependencies, then provide a step-by-step setup guide.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"110F:3AF65D:BF729E:DF6A27:69FE84F6"},"id":"56144c4b-3915-45d5-b755-e96463e8f23a","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:14.598Z","parentId":"9e60cd41-3dbf-4d90-98d8-735c06662e92"}
