{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2f0d172e-ebd8-4a53-99ec-4804f8578e0d","content":"You have .NET 10 and 11-preview. Here's the full plan:\n\n---\n\n### Step 1 — Determine required versions from your workload\n\n```bash\n# Install the MAUI Android workload (pulls matching Android bindings)\ndotnet workload install maui-android\n\n# After install, inspect the resolved Android manifest to find\n# the exact API level, build-tools, and JDK version it expects:\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nThe workload metadata (in `sdk-manifests/` under your SDK path) will reference specific Android API levels (e.g., `android-34`) and minimum JDK version (typically **JDK 17** for current MAUI).\n\n### Step 2 — Install JDK 17\n\n```bash\nsudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y openjdk-17-jdk\nexport JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk-amd64\n```\n\nWhy 17: The Android Gradle/d8/R8 toolchain in recent MAUI requires JDK 17. Verify with:\n```bash\ngrep -ri \"JavaSdkVersion\\|java_version\\|JdkVersion\" \\\n  /usr/share/dotnet/sdk-manifests/\n```\n\n### Step 3 — Install Android SDK (command-line tools only)\n\n```bash\n# Get the latest command-line tools URL from:\n#   https://developer.android.com/studio#command-line-tools-only\nCMDLINE_TOOLS_URL=\"https://dl.google.com/android/repository/commandlinetools-linux-11076708_latest.zip\"\n\nexport ANDROID_HOME=$HOME/android-sdk\nmkdir -p \"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools\"\ncurl -sSL \"$CMDLINE_TOOLS_URL\" -o /tmp/cmdline-tools.zip\nunzip -q /tmp/cmdline-tools.zip -d \"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools\"\nmv \"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools/cmdline-tools\" \"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools/latest\"\nexport PATH=\"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools/latest/bin:$ANDROID_HOME/platform-tools:$PATH\"\n```\n\n### Step 4 — Accept licenses & install platform packages\n\n```bash\n# Find the exact API level your project targets — check your .csproj:\ngrep TargetFramework *.csproj\n# e.g. net10.0-android35 → you need platform android-35\n\nyes | sdkmanager --licenses\nsdkmanager \"platform-tools\" \\\n           \"platforms;android-35\" \\\n           \"build-tools;35.0.0\"\n```\n\n**How to find the right build-tools version:** Run `sdkmanager --list | grep build-tools` and pick the one matching your platform level.\n\n### Step 5 — Set environment variables persistently\n\n```bash\nexport ANDROID_HOME=$HOME/android-sdk\nexport ANDROID_SDK_ROOT=$ANDROID_HOME   # legacy alias some tools check\nexport JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk-amd64\nexport PATH=\"$ANDROID_HOME/cmdline-tools/latest/bin:$ANDROID_HOME/platform-tools:$PATH\"\n```\n\n### Step 6 — Build\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -f net10.0-android -c Release\n# or publish a signed APK:\ndotnet publish -f net10.0-android -c Release \\\n  -p:AndroidKeyStore=true \\\n  -p:AndroidSigningKeyStore=mykey.keystore \\\n  -p:AndroidSigningKeyAlias=myalias \\\n  -p:AndroidSigningKeyPass=env:KEYSTORE_PASS \\\n  -p:AndroidSigningStorePass=env:KEYSTORE_PASS\n```\n\n---\n\n### Quick version-discovery cheat sheet\n\n| What | How to find the right version |\n|---|---|\n| **API level** | `grep TargetFramework *.csproj` → `android35` = API 35 |\n| **Build-tools** | `sdkmanager --list \\| grep build-tools` → match major to API |\n| **JDK** | `grep -ri JdkVersion /usr/share/dotnet/sdk-manifests/` |\n| **Workload** | `dotnet workload search maui` → shows available versions |\n\nThe key insight: let `dotnet workload install maui-android` drive your version choices — it declares what Android API and JDK it needs, and you install those to match.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ba5a5087-7245-4b33-9568-673a87dc8cb8","outputTokens":1109,"requestId":"111F:2D7D24:C37882:E37390:69FE8503"},"id":"59469875-4575-48a2-a6cf-4c9906075356","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:36.418Z","parentId":"447e6b72-61d3-4fb8-951e-8adf37a1d829"}
